Dear Team,
As discussed and validated during implementation activity, enabling restrictive/default deny firewall policy uniformly across all Oracle RAC interfaces caused Oracle ASM/RAC interconnect communication failure resulting in cluster instability and node eviction (ORA-29740 / IPC timeout).
Further, Oracle support/DBA team has also confirmed that firewall or third-party filtering should not be enabled on RAC interconnect/private communication interfaces and recommended exclusion for:
• RAC interconnect/private interfaces
• ASM communication
• GI binaries
• RDBMS binaries
• ADR home
• ACFS/ASM-related communication paths
Post validation, the following approach is recommended for secure and stable implementation:
• Public/client-facing interfaces will remain under restricted firewall zone with only required ports/services allowed.
• RAC private interconnect and ASM communication interfaces should remain under trusted/internal zone or excluded from restrictive filtering to avoid cluster heartbeat interruption.
• firewalld service can remain enabled with controlled segmentation and explicit allow rules for public access.
• Network-level controls such as VLAN segregation, upstream firewall policies, restricted routing, IDS/IPS, and access controls continue to provide compensating security controls.
This approach aligns operational stability with security hardening requirements while preventing Oracle RAC service disruption.
Hence, request you to review and modify the SCD observation/control applicability for Oracle RAC/ASM clustered servers accordingly.